														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4102683">
									

<p>SCP-343 isn't God, but not being able to see SCP-682 actually kinda makes sense anyway.<br />
Reality benders do just that: bend reality. But SCP-682 is not from or a part of the Foundation's iteration of reality. According to Gears it's from somewhere totally different where it's the norm and humans would be the monsters<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-544763-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-544763-1')">1</a></sup>. Despite being damn-near omnipotent in their given range of effect Type Greens are still limited to their understanding of reality. A SCP object is something that defies understood reality. They might be able to create &quot;impossible&quot; things but SCPs aren't even really on the scale of &quot;possible&quot; and &quot;impossible&quot; and to think otherwise is the start of Filbuson Syndrome.</p>
<p>That's part of the way to combat reality-benders. You can't out-gun them so you have to out-crazy them. If a reality warper did somehow gain the ability to generate things &quot;beyond it's imagination&quot; than there's some other ectoentropic force at play. Either one they've created or summoned. They might be able to create a construct that reacts in ways even beyond their understanding but at that point it's not them anymore, and it's not human anymore.</p>
<p>Now that begs the question, if one of the most powerful reality warpers doesn't react to SCP-682 what does that make SCP-053? And going on that train of thought: If reality bender + monster = neutral reaction, why does Dr. Clef + reality bender also equal neutral to no reaction?</p>
