					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/pedantique" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3118444); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3118444&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226129" alt="Pedantique" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3118444)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/pedantique" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3118444); return false;" >Pedantique</a></span> <span class="odate time_1526536370 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">17 May 2018 05:52</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3803004">
									

<p>Since there's just the singular thread now, here's why I think these posts are always kind of silly:</p>
<p>I don't think 682 is best read as a puzzle to be unlocked, where there's some solution that would let the Foundation destroy it once and for all. That assumes some kind of inherent truth to the setting, and proposing solutions always feels silly since no one is going to respond &quot;by jove, why didn't we think of that! Problem solved.&quot;</p>
<p>I think it's much more interesting to read 682 as a personification of the reason the Foundation doesn't try to destroy anomalies like the GOC does. Attempts to do so here will fail. Attempts will often make it worse. No matter how brilliant and elaborate any proposed termination method is, there's an equally good way for it to be subverted. The entire situation captures a sense of futility and struggle that would be undermined if there was some kind of accepted termination method.</p>
<p>There's plenty of interesting conceptual space for stories where 682 <em>does</em> die, but I doubt many of those would focus heavily on the details of whatever methods were employed to that end.</p>

							</div>

								
					
